('economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets:exam:13cab34c', 'economics', 'economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets', '2.1 The Role of Markets', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q2", "question": "Using the information in the pie charts, which one of the following statements must be true?", "options": ["Primary sector output in Sierra Leone has been increasing", "Sierra Leone produces more primary sector products than Sweden", "Swedish tertiary sector output is bigger than the secondary and primary combined", "The two economies are the same size"], "caseStudy": "<img src=\"/images/economics/2-1-gdp-sector-pies-extracted.png\" alt=\"Two pie charts from the OCR exam paper. Sweden: GDP composition by sector — primary 1.8%, secondary 33.3%, tertiary 64.9%. Sierra Leone: primary 61.6%, secondary 6.3%, tertiary 32.3%\" style=\"display:block;width:100%;max-width:480px;margin:14px auto;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:8px;background:#fff;padding:6px;\" />\n<p>Information about what different countries produce can be useful for investment decisions.</p>", "hint": "The pies show PERCENTAGES of each economy, not amounts — so you can''t compare between countries or over time. Which statement only uses percentages within ONE country?", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO2)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: C — Swedish tertiary sector output is bigger than the secondary and primary combined</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Within Sweden: tertiary is 64.9%, and secondary + primary is 33.3% + 1.8% = 35.1%. So C must be true.</li>\n<li>A needs data over time; B and D need the actual sizes of the two economies — percentages alone can''t tell you either.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets:exam:9c249b1a', 'economics', 'economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets', '2.1 The Role of Markets', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q3", "question": "Which one of the following is determined in a product market?", "options": ["The output of desks", "The quantity of carpenters", "The rent of a field", "The wages of plumbers"], "hint": "Three options are prices/quantities of FACTORS (labour, land). Which one is a finished good?", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO1b)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: A — The output of desks</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Desks are finished goods, sold in the product market.</li>\n<li>Carpenters and plumbers (labour) and a field (land) are factors of production — their quantities, wages and rent are set in factor markets.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets:exam:3b5fd502', 'economics', 'economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets', '2.1 The Role of Markets', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q4", "question": "Economies of scale occur when a producer increases output and...", "options": ["Average costs fall", "Gets existing staff to work overtime", "Pays more for its raw materials", "Takes on more workers"], "hint": "Economies of scale are about what happens to the cost PER UNIT as output grows.", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO1a)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: A — Average costs fall</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Economies of scale mean that as output rises, the cost per unit (average cost) falls.</li>\n<li>Overtime, dearer raw materials and extra workers describe things a growing firm might do — not economies of scale themselves.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets:exam:ed8dc7f0', 'economics', 'economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets', '2.1 The Role of Markets', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q6", "question": "What would be a direct benefit for these workers?", "options": ["Creates jobs", "Increased skill", "Less boredom", "Unemployment"], "caseStudy": "Two workers asked their employer if they can specialise, instead of doing several different jobs.", "hint": "''Direct benefit FOR THE WORKERS'' — and careful: specialising usually makes work MORE repetitive, not less.", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO1b)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: B — Increased skill</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Doing one task repeatedly builds expertise — the direct benefit to the workers themselves.</li>\n<li>Less boredom (C) is wrong — repetitive work usually means MORE boredom, which is a cost of specialisation.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Examiner''s Comments</h5>\n<p>Most of the candidates gave B as the correct response to this question.</p>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets:exam:a85241b5', 'economics', 'economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets', '2.1 The Role of Markets', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q7", "question": "According to an economist, what is this an example of?", "options": ["A market", "An exchange", "C Demand", "Supply"], "caseStudy": "A clothing retailer decides to sell its goods to consumers on the internet.", "hint": "Buyers and sellers coming together online — what do economists call any arrangement like that?", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO2)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: A — A market</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>A market is anywhere buyers and sellers come together — it does not need a physical location.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Examiner''s Comments</h5>\n<p>Most of the candidates gave A as the correct response to this question.</p>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets:exam:6c890353', 'economics', 'economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets', '2.1 The Role of Markets', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q8", "question": "This is an example of...", "options": ["A bigger market", "Efficient use of resources", "Improved standards of living", "Time saving"], "caseStudy": "The town of Barrow-in-Furness specialises in the manufacturing industry.", "hint": "A REGION specialising means using its land, labour and capital where they work best — which option says that?", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO1b)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: B — Efficient use of resources</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Regional specialisation means the area concentrates its resources on the industry they are best suited to — the efficient use of resources.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Examiner''s Comments</h5>\n<p>A high percentage of candidates gave Option B as the correct response to this question.</p>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets:exam:575e8b0a', 'economics', 'economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets', '2.1 The Role of Markets', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q11", "question": "This charity event is an example of a...", "options": ["Market", "Monopoly", "Primary sector activity", "Producer"], "caseStudy": "A beekeeper has been invited to sell the honey produced by their bees at a charity event in the local village hall.", "hint": "Buyers and sellers coming together to exchange goods — wherever it happens. What is that called?", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO2)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: A — Market</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>The event brings together buyers and sellers to exchange goods — that makes it a market, whatever the location.</li>\n<li>Producing the honey is primary sector activity, but the EVENT is where it is sold — a market.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Examiner''s Comments</h5>\n<p>A very high percentage of candidates gave Option A as the correct response to this question.</p>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets:exam:b33dce72', 'economics', 'economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets', '2.1 The Role of Markets', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q13", "question": "Buyers and sellers of a good on a website is an example of...", "options": ["A market", "Competition", "Specialisation", "The secondary sector"], "hint": "Buyers + sellers + exchange = ? (The location doesn''t matter.)", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO1b)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: A — A market</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>A market is anywhere buyers and sellers come together to exchange goods — including a website.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Examiner''s Comments</h5>\n<p>Most candidates gave Option A as the correct response to this question.</p>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets:exam:72d6e94b', 'economics', 'economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets', '2.1 The Role of Markets', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q14", "question": "What is an activity in a factor market?", "options": ["Firms buying a greater quantity of finished goods", "Firms employing more engineers", "Firms producing output using advanced technology", "Households seeking to buy more electric cars"], "hint": "The factor market is where factors of production are bought — which option involves buying LABOUR?", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO1b)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: B — Firms employing more engineers</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Employing engineers is buying labour — a factor of production — so it happens in the factor market.</li>\n<li>Buying finished goods and electric cars are product-market activities; producing output is not a market activity at all.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Examiner''s Comments</h5>\n<p>Many candidates gave Option B as the correct response to this question.</p>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets:exam:437124cc', 'economics', 'economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets', '2.1 The Role of Markets', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q15", "question": "In which sector of the economy would a boat building firm be placed?", "options": ["Free market", "Primary", "Secondary", "Tertiary"], "hint": "Building boats = manufacturing raw materials into a finished good. Which sector is that?", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO1b)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: C — Secondary</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Boat building is manufacturing — turning raw materials into finished goods — so it belongs to the secondary sector.</li>\n<li>''Free market'' is not a sector of the economy at all.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Examiner''s Comments</h5>\n<p>Most candidates gave Option C as the correct response to this question.</p>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets:exam:a6224e8e', 'economics', 'economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets', '2.1 The Role of Markets', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q19", "question": "Which of the following is an example of a factor market?", "options": ["A toy company hires more workers to increase production", "A toy company sells a new toy to a consumer", "Beth sells her second-hand car to Jack", "The government provides healthcare free for all users"], "hint": "Which option involves buying a FACTOR OF PRODUCTION (like labour) rather than a finished product?", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO2)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: A — A toy company hires more workers to increase production</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Hiring workers is buying labour — a factor of production — so it happens in the factor market.</li>\n<li>Selling a toy or a second-hand car happens in product markets; free healthcare is government provision, not a market.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets:exam:72887874', 'economics', 'economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets', '2.1 The Role of Markets', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q20", "question": "For an exchange to take place, which of the following is essential?", "options": ["At least one buyer and one seller", "Government permission to trade", "Specialisation", "The payment of money"], "hint": "Strip it back to basics — swapping goods without money (barter) still counts as exchange. What CAN''T you do without?", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO1b)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: A — At least one buyer and one seller</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Exchange only needs someone to give and someone to receive — money is not essential (barter is exchange too), and neither is government permission or specialisation.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets:exam:d9a45c9f', 'economics', 'economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets', '2.1 The Role of Markets', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q22", "question": "Which of the following statements is correct about a school teacher''s output?", "options": ["It is equal to zero because no goods are produced", "It is part of the primary sector", "It is part of the secondary sector", "It is part of the tertiary sector"], "hint": "Services ARE output — which sector provides services?", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO2)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: D — It is part of the tertiary sector</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>A teacher produces a service — education — and services are real output in the tertiary sector.</li>\n<li>Option A is the trap: output is not zero just because nothing physical is made.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets:exam:574cb89b', 'economics', 'economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets', '2.1 The Role of Markets', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q23", "question": "Which of the following statements is true for this economy?", "options": ["The primary sector is the largest", "The tertiary sector is the largest", "The tertiary sector is the same size as the primary sector", "The value of the primary sector is £70 billion"], "caseStudy": "An economy''s output by sector of industry: Agriculture £70 billion; Mining £20 billion; Manufacturing £80 billion; Services £70 billion.", "hint": "Careful — the primary sector is agriculture PLUS mining. Add them before comparing.", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO2)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: A — The primary sector is the largest</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Primary = agriculture (£70bn) + mining (£20bn) = £90bn — larger than manufacturing (£80bn, secondary) and services (£70bn, tertiary).</li>\n<li>Option D is the trap for anyone who forgets mining is primary too.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets:exam:aa90e594', 'economics', 'economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets', '2.1 The Role of Markets', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q24", "question": "Which of these is classified as part of the output of the primary sector?", "options": ["Buildings", "Dishwashers", "Haircuts", "Oil"], "hint": "Which one comes straight out of the ground or sea?", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO1b)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: D — Oil</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Oil is extracted directly from natural resources — primary sector.</li>\n<li>Buildings and dishwashers are manufactured (secondary); haircuts are a service (tertiary).</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Examiner''s Comments</h5>\n<p>A very high percentage of candidates gave Option D as the correct response to this question.</p>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets:exam:6a864cd0', 'economics', 'economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets', '2.1 The Role of Markets', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q25", "question": "Which of the following is true for all factor markets?", "options": ["Demand is derived", "Final goods and services are bought and sold", "Households are the buyers", "Prices are determined by the government"], "hint": "Factors aren''t wanted for their own sake — the demand for them comes from somewhere else. What''s that called?", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO1b)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: A — Demand is derived</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Demand for any factor of production comes from demand for the products it helps make — derived demand is true of every factor market.</li>\n<li>Final goods belong to the product market; in factor markets, FIRMS are usually the buyers.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets:exam:55857817', 'economics', 'economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets', '2.1 The Role of Markets', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q27", "question": "Which of the following is an example of a market in operation?", "options": ["A country experiences inflation", "Consumers buy services from producers", "The government taxes producers", "Workers pay taxes out of their wages"], "hint": "A market in operation = buying and selling actually happening. Which option is a purchase?", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO1b)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: B — Consumers buy services from producers</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Buyers (consumers) and sellers (producers) exchanging services — a market in operation.</li>\n<li>Inflation and taxes are economic events, not market exchanges.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets:exam:4c4504e2', 'economics', 'economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets', '2.1 The Role of Markets', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q28", "question": "A business which operates in the secondary sector...", "options": ["Grows agricultural products", "Manufactures goods", "Mines for commodities such as copper ore", "Produces services"], "hint": "Growing and mining are primary; services are tertiary. What''s left?", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO1b)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: B — Manufactures goods</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>The secondary sector manufactures — it turns raw materials into finished goods.</li>\n<li>Growing crops and mining are primary; services are tertiary.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets:exam:221799b3', 'economics', 'economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets', '2.1 The Role of Markets', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q29", "question": "Which conclusion can be made from the data?", "options": ["The economy is smaller than most other economies", "The secondary sector is four times larger than the primary sector", "The tertiary sector is the fastest growing sector", "The total value of national output is £100"], "caseStudy": "An economy''s share of national output in a year: Primary 10%; Secondary 40%; Tertiary 50%.", "hint": "The data is percentages for ONE year — you can''t conclude anything about growth, size in £, or other economies. What CAN you compare?", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO1b)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: B — The secondary sector is four times larger than the primary sector</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>40% is four times 10% — that comparison works within the year''s percentages.</li>\n<li>Growth needs data over time; the economy''s size in £ and comparisons with other economies can''t be read from percentages.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets:exam:78003b54', 'economics', 'economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets', '2.1 The Role of Markets', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q30", "question": "Which of these workers produces output in the primary sector?", "options": ["A farmer", "A nurse", "A waiter in a restaurant", "A worker on a building site"], "hint": "Who works directly with natural resources?", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO2)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: A — A farmer</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Farming uses natural resources directly — primary sector.</li>\n<li>A nurse and a waiter provide services (tertiary); a building-site worker is in construction (secondary).</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets:exam:24c5cb42', 'economics', 'economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets', '2.1 The Role of Markets', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q31", "question": "Which of the following would be a direct benefit of this for the producer?", "options": ["Creation of jobs for the local skilled workers", "Increase of job satisfaction of the workers", "Increase of productivity of the workers", "Greater likelihood that workers will change jobs"], "caseStudy": "A clothing manufacturer has decided to specialise in making trousers for women.", "hint": "''Direct benefit FOR THE PRODUCER'' — two options benefit the workers, one is a cost. Which one helps the firm''s output?", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO1b)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: C — Increase of productivity of the workers</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Higher worker productivity means more output per worker — a direct benefit to the producer.</li>\n<li>Jobs and job satisfaction benefit workers/the area; workers changing jobs more often is a COST to the producer.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Examiner''s Comments</h5>\n<p>Most candidates gave Option C as the correct response to this question.</p>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets:mcq:ce177ed7', 'economics', 'economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets', '2.1 The Role of Markets', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Which of these is NOT a market?", "options": ["A farmers'' market", "An auction website", "A stock exchange", "A factory production line"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "explain": "A market needs buyers and sellers exchanging something. A production line makes goods — nothing is bought or sold there."}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets:mcq:fc2ef06b', 'economics', 'economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets', '2.1 The Role of Markets', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "A fisherman catching fish at sea works in which sector?", "options": ["Primary", "Tertiary", "Financial", "Secondary"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Fishing extracts natural resources directly, so it''s primary sector — the start of the chain of production."}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets:mcq:976cf691', 'economics', 'economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets', '2.1 The Role of Markets', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "A hairdresser works in which sector?", "options": ["Tertiary", "Secondary", "Primary", "Manufacturing"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "A haircut is a service (intangible), so hairdressing is tertiary sector."}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets:mcq:924edb76', 'economics', 'economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets', '2.1 The Role of Markets', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Which of these is the best example of the difference between a good and a service?", "options": ["A good is tangible (you can touch it), a service is intangible", "A good is made abroad, a service is made in the UK", "A good is cheap, a service is expensive", "A good is bought by firms, a service by consumers"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Goods are physical things like cars and phones; services, like education or banking, cannot be touched."}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets:mcq:34483dcd', 'economics', 'economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets', '2.1 The Role of Markets', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Wages are set in which market?", "options": ["The factor market", "The product market", "The stock market", "The currency market"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Labour is a factor of production, so wages — the price of labour — are set in the factor market."}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets:mcq:0f61e665', 'economics', 'economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets', '2.1 The Role of Markets', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Demand for delivery drivers rises because more people are ordering takeaway food. This shows that demand for labour is...", "options": ["Independent of the product market", "Derived from the demand for the product", "Unlimited", "Set by the government"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "Drivers aren''t demanded for their own sake — the demand comes from (is derived from) demand for the takeaway food they deliver."}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets:mcq:56fb9a4e', 'economics', 'economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets', '2.1 The Role of Markets', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "In the circular flow of income, households receive wages from firms and use them to...", "options": ["Buy goods and services from firms", "Supply raw materials", "Pay other households", "Set the equilibrium price"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Households spend their wages in the product market — and that spending gives firms the income to keep paying wages. That''s the circular flow."}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets:mcq:dfb1cc80', 'economics', 'economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets', '2.1 The Role of Markets', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "A car factory divides production so each worker does one task — one fits doors, another paints. This is called...", "options": ["Derived demand", "The price mechanism", "Exchange", "Division of labour"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "explain": "Dividing a process into separate tasks with each worker specialising in one part is the division of labour."}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets:mcq:613d773d', 'economics', 'economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets', '2.1 The Role of Markets', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "A region that specialises in one industry faces which main risk?", "options": ["It cannot trade with other regions", "Its workers become too skilled", "Prices in the region always rise", "If demand for that industry falls, unemployment rises across the whole area"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "explain": "Specialised regions depend on one industry — when steel or shipbuilding declined, whole towns suffered high unemployment."}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets:mcq:16338890', 'economics', 'economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets', '2.1 The Role of Markets', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "When there is excess supply in a free market, what happens to price and why?", "options": ["It falls, so that quantity demanded rises until it equals supply", "It rises, because the product is scarce", "It falls to zero", "It stays the same, because the government fixes it"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Unsold stock pushes sellers to cut the price; as the price falls, demand rises and supply falls until the market returns to equilibrium."}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets:tf:83e70c76', 'economics', 'economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets', '2.1 The Role of Markets', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "A market must be a physical place, like a town square."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "A market is anywhere buyers and sellers come together — including websites, auctions and phone apps."}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets:tf:03344e22', 'economics', 'economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets', '2.1 The Role of Markets', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "A boat building firm is in the secondary sector."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "Boat building is manufacturing — turning raw materials into finished goods — so it''s secondary sector."}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets:tf:231aab5e', 'economics', 'economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets', '2.1 The Role of Markets', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "A school teacher''s output is zero because no goods are produced."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "Producing a service IS producing output — teaching is part of the tertiary sector. (This is a real OCR exam trap.)"}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets:tf:bf809884', 'economics', 'economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets', '2.1 The Role of Markets', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "The factor market is where factors of production, like labour, are bought and sold."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "Correct — firms hire workers, buy raw materials and buy equipment in factor markets."}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets:tf:8b880161', 'economics', 'economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets', '2.1 The Role of Markets', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "The factor market is another name for the primary sector."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "They''re completely different ideas: the factor market is where inputs are traded; the primary sector is a type of production. A real OCR mark scheme flags this exact confusion."}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets:tf:9246bc4a', 'economics', 'economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets', '2.1 The Role of Markets', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "Demand in all factor markets is derived demand."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "Factors are only demanded because the products they help make are demanded — that''s what ''derived'' means. (A real OCR exam answer.)"}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets:tf:49b264f6', 'economics', 'economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets', '2.1 The Role of Markets', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "The direct benefit of specialisation for a worker is less boredom."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "It''s the opposite — repetitive work usually means MORE boredom. The direct benefit is increased skill."}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets:tf:15020be0', 'economics', 'economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets', '2.1 The Role of Markets', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "For an exchange to take place, all that''s essential is at least one buyer and one seller."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "Exchange doesn''t require money (barter counts), government permission, or specialisation — just a buyer and a seller. (A real OCR exam question.)"}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets:learn:470679a5', 'economics', 'economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets', '2.1 The Role of Markets', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "What is a market?", "reading": "<h4>The definition</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>A market is a way of <strong>bringing together buyers and sellers</strong> to exchange goods and services.</li>\n<li>It does NOT have to be a physical place — a shop, a weekly town market, an auction, a website and the stock market are all markets.</li>\n<li>Buyers and sellers interact to <strong>set a price</strong>, based on demand and supply.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Characteristics of a market (real 2-mark exam question)</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>It contains buyers</li>\n<li>It contains sellers</li>\n<li>It is where demand and supply meet</li>\n<li>It is where the price is set</li>\n<li>Money changes hands (or goods are swapped — barter)</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>How markets allocate scarce resources: the price mechanism</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Signalling</strong> — rising prices tell producers more resources are needed there. Example: the worldwide computer chip shortage drove prices up, signalling chip firms to invest billions in new factories.</li>\n<li><strong>Rationing</strong> — when something is scarce, the price rises and only those willing and able to pay get it. Example: concert tickets for a popular band.</li>\n<li><strong>Incentivising</strong> — a higher price gives producers a reason to supply more; a lower price gives consumers a reason to buy more.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Equilibrium — where the market settles</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Equilibrium price and quantity</strong> is where quantity demanded exactly equals quantity supplied.</li>\n<li>Above it there is a surplus (excess supply), which pushes the price down. Below it there is a shortage, which pushes the price up.</li>\n<li>So a free market deals with excess supply by <strong>lowering the price until demand equals supply again</strong>.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Price vs worth</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Price</strong> is what everyone pays — it''s the same for every buyer.</li>\n<li><strong>Worth</strong> is how much YOU value it — an ice cream is worth more to you on a hot day, even though the price hasn''t changed.</li>\n<li>In an efficient market, prices reflect the worth of the resources used up in making the product.</li>\n</ul>", "question": "A clothing retailer starts selling its goods to consumers on the internet. To an economist, this is an example of...", "options": ["The secondary sector", "A market", "A planned economy", "Division of labour"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "A market is anywhere buyers and sellers come together — including online. This is a real OCR exam question, and ''a market'' was the answer."}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets:learn:0502211c', 'economics', 'economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets', '2.1 The Role of Markets', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "The three sectors of the economy", "reading": "<h4>Primary sector</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>The <strong>direct use of natural resources</strong> — extracting basic materials from the land and sea.</li>\n<li>Examples: agriculture, fishing, forestry, mining, quarrying, oil extraction.</li>\n<li>It is the START of the chain of production.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Secondary sector</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Manufacturing and construction</strong> — turning raw materials from the primary sector into finished goods.</li>\n<li>Examples: car manufacturing, energy, building houses.</li>\n<li>The key is <strong>adding value</strong> to the raw materials.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Tertiary sector</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Activities that provide a <strong>service</strong>.</li>\n<li>Examples: banking, finance, insurance, education, tourism, health.</li>\n<li>A teacher''s or nurse''s output counts — producing a service IS producing output.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Goods vs services</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Goods are tangible</strong> — you can touch them (cars, phones).</li>\n<li><strong>Services are intangible</strong> — you cannot touch them (education, banking).</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>UK trends worth knowing</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>The UK''s secondary sector has declined sharply since the 1970s, mainly due to low-cost competition from abroad.</li>\n<li>Services are now the most important part of the UK economy — the UK exports more services than it imports.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>The sectors are interdependent</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>One firm''s output becomes another firm''s input.</li>\n<li>A farmer (primary) relies on food manufacturers (secondary) to buy the crops; the supermarket (tertiary) relies on the manufacturer for products to sell.</li>\n</ul>", "question": "In which sector would a boat building firm be placed?", "options": ["Secondary", "Primary", "Tertiary", "Free market"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Building boats is manufacturing — turning raw materials into a finished good — so it''s the secondary sector. (A real OCR exam question.)"}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets:learn:3c5d6022', 'economics', 'economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets', '2.1 The Role of Markets', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Factor and product markets — and how they depend on each other", "reading": "<h4>The product market</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>The market for <strong>finished goods and services</strong> — supermarkets, high street shops, online stores.</li>\n<li>Buyers can be consumers, other businesses, or the government.</li>\n<li>Prices are set by supply and demand.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>The factor market</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>The market where the <strong>factors of production are bought and sold</strong>.</li>\n<li>The labour market: households supply their labour to firms in exchange for wages.</li>\n<li>Also includes markets for raw materials (like oil) and for capital equipment.</li>\n<li><strong>Watch out:</strong> the factor market is NOT the same as the primary sector — a real OCR mark scheme flags this exact confusion.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Derived demand — the key idea</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Demand in the factor market is <strong>derived</strong> — factors aren''t wanted for their own sake, only because the products they make are in demand.</li>\n<li>Example: rising demand for smartphones → rising demand for lithium and cobalt (raw materials) → rising demand for miners and computer scientists (labour).</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Interdependence: the circular flow of income</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Households supply labour to firms (factor market)…</li>\n<li>…firms use that labour to produce goods and services…</li>\n<li>…firms pay wages to households…</li>\n<li>…households spend those wages on goods and services (product market)…</li>\n<li>…and that spending gives firms the income to keep employing people. The cycle continues.</li>\n</ul>", "question": "A toy company hires more workers to increase production. Which market does this happen in?", "options": ["The factor market", "The primary sector", "The product market", "The stock market"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Hiring workers is buying labour — a factor of production — so it happens in the factor market. Selling the toys to consumers happens in the product market. (A real OCR exam question.)"}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets:learn:052c5819', 'economics', 'economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets', '2.1 The Role of Markets', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Specialisation and exchange — for workers, producers, regions and countries", "reading": "<h4>The definitions</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Specialisation</strong> — when workers, producers, regions or countries concentrate on one particular task, product or industry.</li>\n<li><strong>Division of labour</strong> — when the tasks in a production process are divided up between workers, with each specialising in one part.</li>\n<li><strong>Exchange</strong> — trading products with others. All that''s essential for an exchange is at least one buyer and one seller.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Workers</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Benefits:</strong> increased skill (the DIRECT benefit), fewer mistakes, higher quality work, potentially higher pay.</li>\n<li><strong>Costs:</strong> boredom from repetitive work, demotivation, de-skilling — being unable to do other kinds of work if demand falls.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Producers (firms)</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Benefits:</strong> higher productivity and output, lower unit costs, economies of scale, higher quality, a stronger reputation, time saved.</li>\n<li><strong>Costs:</strong> bored workers leave more often (higher recruitment and training costs), a less flexible workforce, over-dependence on one product.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Regions</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Benefits:</strong> efficient use of the region''s resources, jobs and income, a reputation for the industry (e.g. Barrow-in-Furness and shipbuilding).</li>\n<li><strong>Costs:</strong> the region becomes reliant on one industry — if it declines, unemployment hits the whole area (e.g. steel towns).</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Countries</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Benefits:</strong> countries produce what they''re best at (France and Italy''s climate suits wine; the Middle East has oil), more to trade, higher GDP from exports.</li>\n<li><strong>Costs:</strong> reliance on worldwide demand, which can change; more reliant on imports of everything else.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Why exchange makes everyone better off</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Specialists produce better quality at lower cost.</li>\n<li>By trading with each other, all parties get higher quality and lower costs than if they tried to make everything themselves — total economic welfare rises.</li>\n</ul>", "question": "Two workers ask their employer if they can specialise instead of doing several different jobs. What is the DIRECT benefit for these workers?", "options": ["Increased skill", "It creates jobs", "Higher profits", "Less boredom"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Doing one task repeatedly builds expertise — increased skill is the direct benefit to the workers themselves. (A real OCR exam question; specialised work usually means MORE boredom, not less.)"}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets:misc:1609af10', 'economics', 'economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets', '2.1 The Role of Markets', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> The factor market is the same as the primary sector.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> The FACTOR market is where inputs (labour, raw materials, capital) are bought and sold. The PRIMARY sector is a type of production — extracting natural resources. A mining company operates in the primary sector, but when it hires miners it is buying labour in the factor market. This confusion comes straight from a real OCR mark scheme misconception box.</p>", "question": "A supermarket (tertiary sector) hires ten new checkout assistants. Which market is the hiring happening in?", "options": ["The factor market", "The primary sector", "The tertiary market", "The product market"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Hiring workers is buying labour, so it happens in the factor market — even though the supermarket itself is a tertiary-sector business. Sector and market are different ideas."}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets:misc:1141f0a7', 'economics', 'economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets', '2.1 The Role of Markets', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> When a question asks about the benefits of specialisation, any benefit will do.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> The question always names WHO the benefit is for — the workers, the firm, the region or the country — and answers about the wrong group score NOTHING. In one real exam, ''boredom in workers who only specialise in one trade'' was given 0 marks on a question about the cost to the BUSINESS. The fix: chain it to the right group — \"workers get bored, SO more of them leave, SO the business pays higher recruitment and training costs.\"</p>", "question": "A question asks for one cost TO A SMALL BUSINESS of specialisation by its workers. Which answer earns marks?", "options": ["\"Workers get bored, so more leave, and the business faces higher recruitment costs\"", "\"Workers become deskilled\"", "\"Workers get bored doing the same task\"", "\"Workers may want more pay\""]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Only the second answer lands the cost on the BUSINESS. The others stop at the effect on workers — that''s the exact mistake that scored 0 in the real exam."}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets:misc:8d703d4f', 'economics', 'economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets', '2.1 The Role of Markets', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> A market has to be a physical marketplace.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> A market is any way of bringing buyers and sellers together — a shop, an auction, a website, a catalogue, or a charity event in a village hall (a real OCR exam example). What makes it a market is the buying and selling, not the location.</p>", "question": "A beekeeper sells honey at a charity event in the local village hall. The event is an example of...", "options": ["A market", "A monopoly", "Primary sector activity", "A producer"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Buyers and sellers came together to exchange goods — that''s a market, wherever it happens. (A real OCR exam question.)"}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets:misc:fb05a8e5', 'economics', 'economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets', '2.1 The Role of Markets', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> People who provide services (like teachers or nurses) don''t really produce anything.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> Services ARE output. Goods are tangible and services are intangible, but both are products. A teacher''s output is education — part of the tertiary sector, which is the biggest part of the UK economy. The real OCR distractor ''output is zero because no goods are produced'' catches students who forget this.</p>", "question": "Which sector does a nurse''s output belong to?", "options": ["Secondary", "Primary", "None — services aren''t output", "Tertiary"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "explain": "Healthcare is a service, and services are real output in the tertiary sector."}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets:misc:3e38cbe5', 'economics', 'economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets', '2.1 The Role of Markets', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Equilibrium means the price and the quantity are equal to each other.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> Equilibrium is where quantity DEMANDED equals quantity SUPPLIED — not where price equals quantity. Level 0 answer: \"it''s where price and quantity are equal\" (a real muddle examiners reported). Level 1 answer: \"where the supply and demand curves meet.\" Full-marks answer: \"where quantity supplied exactly matches quantity demanded, so there is no shortage or surplus and no pressure on the price to change.\"</p>", "question": "What is true at the equilibrium price?", "options": ["Supply is always rising", "Firms make no profit", "Price equals quantity", "Quantity demanded equals quantity supplied"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "explain": "At equilibrium the market clears: everything supplied is demanded, so there''s no surplus or shortage and no pressure on price to change."}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets:misc:1624d2ef', 'economics', 'economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets', '2.1 The Role of Markets', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> A ''market'' and a ''market economy'' are the same thing.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> A market is a single mechanism — one place/way that buyers and sellers of a particular product meet. A market ECONOMY is a whole system where most resources are allocated by market forces. The UK has thousands of individual markets, but as an economy it''s mixed, not a pure market economy.</p>", "question": "Which sentence uses the terms correctly?", "options": ["\"The market for coffee is one market operating within the UK''s mixed economy\"", "\"A market economy contains no markets\"", "\"The UK housing market is a mixed economy\"", "\"Every market is an economy\""]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Individual markets (coffee, housing, labour) operate inside a whole economy. The economy is the system; a market is one mechanism within it."}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets:tips:d2ae01de', 'economics', 'economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets', '2.1 The Role of Markets', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "tip — Answer for the RIGHT group — this paper''s biggest mark-killer", "reading": "<p>This topic''s exam questions constantly name WHO the costs or benefits are for — and examiners report students losing everything by answering about the wrong group:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>\"one cost <strong>for a small business</strong> of specialisation by its workers\" — answers about the workers scored <strong>0</strong></li>\n<li>\"evaluate the extent to which specialisation would benefit <strong>workers</strong> in Oxbria\" — must be about the workers, not firms</li>\n<li>\"the benefits of specialisation <strong>for Calwith Farmers</strong>\" — answers about workers didn''t reach the higher levels</li>\n<li>\"the advantages... <strong>for Westumbria</strong>\" (the region) — answers about the businesses often got no marks at all</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p><strong>❌ 0 marks (real exam answer):</strong> \"Boredom in workers who only specialise in one trade due to repetitiveness\" — on a question asking the cost to the BUSINESS.</p>\n\n<p><strong>✅ Full marks:</strong> \"Workers get bored doing the same task, so more of them leave — meaning the small business faces higher recruitment and training costs.\"</p>\n\n<p><strong>The fix:</strong> underline the group named in the question, then make sure your final clause lands on THAT group.</p>", "question": "A question asks about the advantages of more production ''for Westumbria'' (a region). Your answer is all about the businesses'' higher profits. What happens?", "options": ["The examiner rewrites it for you", "Often no marks at all — the question asked about the region", "Some marks for effort", "Full marks — profits help everyone"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "Real examiner comment: ''responses that focused on the advantages to small businesses often were not given any marks at all.'' The chain must end on the region — jobs, living standards, attracting firms to the area."}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets:tips:e516e37f', 'economics', 'economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets', '2.1 The Role of Markets', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "tip — Diagram and drawing questions: from 0 to full marks", "reading": "<p>This topic''s paper has BOTH kinds of diagram question:</p>\n\n<p><strong>1. Drawing a curve from a table</strong> (2 marks — \"draw the supply curve for Firm A\"):</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>❌ 0 marks:</strong> a line that ignores the data in the table</li>\n<li><strong>⚠️ 1 mark:</strong> correct points plotted but not joined up, or only one point right</li>\n<li><strong>✅ 2 marks:</strong> all points plotted accurately AND joined with a line</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p><strong>2. ''Using a diagram, analyse...''</strong> (6 marks — the housing question):</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>❌ No diagram at all:</strong> capped at 4 out of 6, no matter how good the writing</li>\n<li><strong>⚠️ Level 2:</strong> correct diagram, but the writing never refers to it</li>\n<li><strong>✅ Level 3:</strong> the writing reads the diagram out loud — \"price rises from p to p1 as shown in the diagram\"</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p><strong>The extra trap in the housing question:</strong> it asks why demand growth causes a <strong>LARGE</strong> increase in price. Real candidates who ignored the word \"large\" couldn''t reach the top level. The answer: supply of housing is INELASTIC (steep curve), so a demand shift moves price a lot and quantity only a little.</p>", "question": "A 6-mark question says ''Using a diagram, analyse...''. You write a brilliant answer but draw no diagram. What''s your maximum mark?", "options": ["6 — the writing is what counts", "4", "2", "5"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "The real mark scheme says ''a maximum of 4 marks if no correct diagram''. Always draw it, label it in context, and refer to it in your writing."}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets:tips:6bc1b227', 'economics', 'economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets', '2.1 The Role of Markets', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "explain — 2-mark definitions: both halves or half marks", "reading": "<p>This topic''s definitions all have TWO required parts — and examiners reported exactly how students dropped to 1 mark:</p>\n\n<p><strong>\"Explain what is meant by a market\":</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>⚠️ 1 mark: \"where things are sold\" — only the selling side. Real examiner comment: many lost a mark \"due to only referring to the selling side of the market and not to buying\".</li>\n<li>✅ 2 marks: \"a way of bringing together buyers AND sellers to buy and sell goods and services\".</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p><strong>\"Explain what is meant by division of labour\":</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>⚠️ 1 mark: \"workers specialising\" — missing the splitting-up idea.</li>\n<li>✅ 2 marks: \"tasks are DIVIDED UP between workers, with each SPECIALISING in one part\".</li>\n<li>❌ 0 marks: just repeating the example from the extract — \"Nina does design and Amir does building\" explains nothing.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p><strong>\"Explain equilibrium price and quantity\":</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>⚠️ 1 mark: \"where the supply and demand curves meet\".</li>\n<li>✅ 2 marks: \"where quantity supplied exactly matches quantity demanded, so there is no pressure on the price to change\".</li>\n</ul>", "question": "Why did ''a market is where things are sold'' score only 1 mark out of 2?", "options": ["It needed a diagram", "Markets aren''t about selling", "It only mentions sellers — a market needs buyers AND sellers", "It''s too short"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "explain": "A market brings together BOTH sides. The real examiner report says candidates lost the second mark by ''only referring to the selling side of the market and not to buying''."}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets:tips:d6880755', 'economics', 'economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets', '2.1 The Role of Markets', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "evaluate — Analyse vs Evaluate — and the extra words after ''evaluate''", "reading": "<p>This paper has BOTH types of 6-marker, sometimes on the same case study:</p>\n\n<p><strong>Analyse</strong> (\"Analyse the benefits of specialisation for Calwith Farmers\"):</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Chains of reasoning: \"specialisation builds expertise, SO productivity rises, MEANING average costs fall, SO they can lower prices and increase sales\"</li>\n<li>No judgement needed. Costs were \"not relevant to this question\" — a real examiner comment about students who wasted time on them.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p><strong>Evaluate</strong> (\"Evaluate the costs and benefits of specialisation to Rwanda\"):</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Both sides, paired — then \"Overall…\" with a reason.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p><strong>The extra requirement after ''evaluate'':</strong> OCR''s own guidance points out that ''evaluate'' always comes with a focus —</p>\n<ul>\n<li>\"evaluate <strong>the extent to which</strong>…\" — say how big/likely, what it depends on</li>\n<li>\"evaluate <strong>the costs</strong>…\" — the costs are the subject, benefits only as counterweight</li>\n<li>\"evaluate <strong>the advantages</strong>…\" — advantages first, weighed against at least one issue</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Evaluating \"in general\" instead of within the question''s specific requirement is what kept real candidates out of Level 3.</p>", "question": "A question says ''Analyse the benefits of specialisation for Calwith Farmers''. Should you also write about the costs?", "options": ["Yes, but briefly", "Yes — always give both sides", "Only in the conclusion", "No — costs were not relevant to this question, says the real examiner report"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "explain": "Analyse questions want developed chains on what was asked — the real examiner report noted that candidates who considered the costs of specialisation were writing material ''not relevant to this question''."}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets:fib:83ef3461', 'economics', 'economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets', '2.1 The Role of Markets', 'fib', 'fib', 2, '{"question": "A market brings together _____ and _____ to exchange goods and services.", "blankOptions": {"B1": ["buyers", "tertiary", "product", "factor"], "B2": ["intangible", "sellers", "secondary", "factor"]}}'::jsonb, '{"blanks": {"B1": "buyers", "B2": "sellers"}}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets:fib:6294ad3c', 'economics', 'economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets', '2.1 The Role of Markets', 'fib', 'fib', 3, '{"question": "The _____ sector extracts natural resources, the _____ sector manufactures goods, and the _____ sector provides services.", "blankOptions": {"B1": ["sellers", "factor", "primary", "supplied"], "B2": ["tangible", "sellers", "derived", "secondary"], "B3": ["tangible", "product", "tertiary", "sellers"]}}'::jsonb, '{"blanks": {"B1": "primary", "B2": "secondary", "B3": "tertiary"}}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets:fib:b4fd957a', 'economics', 'economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets', '2.1 The Role of Markets', 'fib', 'fib', 2, '{"question": "Goods are _____ — you can touch them — while services are _____.", "blankOptions": {"B1": ["derived", "product", "tangible", "buyers"], "B2": ["supplied", "secondary", "tertiary", "intangible"]}}'::jsonb, '{"blanks": {"B1": "tangible", "B2": "intangible"}}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets:fib:bc9db6c5', 'economics', 'economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets', '2.1 The Role of Markets', 'fib', 'fib', 2, '{"question": "Labour is bought and sold in the _____ market, while finished goods are sold in the _____ market.", "blankOptions": {"B1": ["factor", "derived", "intangible", "buyers"], "B2": ["secondary", "product", "derived", "tangible"]}}'::jsonb, '{"blanks": {"B1": "factor", "B2": "product"}}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets:fib:72f732fa', 'economics', 'economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets', '2.1 The Role of Markets', 'fib', 'fib', 1, '{"question": "Demand for workers is a _____ demand, because it comes from demand for the products they make.", "blankOptions": {"B1": ["buyers", "tangible", "derived", "tertiary"]}}'::jsonb, '{"blanks": {"B1": "derived"}}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets:fib:051e20a6', 'economics', 'economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets', '2.1 The Role of Markets', 'fib', 'fib', 1, '{"question": "At the equilibrium price, quantity demanded equals quantity _____.", "blankOptions": {"B1": ["supplied", "sellers", "intangible", "secondary"]}}'::jsonb, '{"blanks": {"B1": "supplied"}}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets:match:fd8cc2b6', 'economics', 'economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets', '2.1 The Role of Markets', 'match', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Which definition matches the key term “Market”?", "options": ["How prices signal, ration and incentivise to allocate scarce resources", "A way of bringing together buyers and sellers to exchange goods and services", "Tangible products that you can touch, like cars and phones", "Activities that provide services, e.g. banking, education and tourism"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "“Market” means: A way of bringing together buyers and sellers to exchange goods and services"}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets:match:db923e6f', 'economics', 'economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets', '2.1 The Role of Markets', 'match', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Which definition matches the key term “Exchange”?", "options": ["Concentrating on one particular task, product or industry", "Where finished goods and services are sold to consumers and firms", "Trading products — needs at least one buyer and one seller", "Manufacturing and construction — turning raw materials into finished goods"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "explain": "“Exchange” means: Trading products — needs at least one buyer and one seller"}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets:match:5da799f4', 'economics', 'economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets', '2.1 The Role of Markets', 'match', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Which definition matches the key term “Price mechanism”?", "options": ["Splitting a production process into tasks, each done by a specialist worker", "Where factors of production, such as labour, are bought and sold", "Manufacturing and construction — turning raw materials into finished goods", "How prices signal, ration and incentivise to allocate scarce resources"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "explain": "“Price mechanism” means: How prices signal, ration and incentivise to allocate scarce resources"}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets:match:28296357', 'economics', 'economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets', '2.1 The Role of Markets', 'match', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Which definition matches the key term “Equilibrium”?", "options": ["Intangible products that you cannot touch, like education and finance", "Demand for a factor that comes from demand for the product it makes", "Manufacturing and construction — turning raw materials into finished goods", "Where quantity demanded exactly equals quantity supplied"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "explain": "“Equilibrium” means: Where quantity demanded exactly equals quantity supplied"}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets:match:9d160e3e', 'economics', 'economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets', '2.1 The Role of Markets', 'match', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Which definition matches the key term “Primary sector”?", "options": ["A way of bringing together buyers and sellers to exchange goods and services", "Demand for a factor that comes from demand for the product it makes", "Manufacturing and construction — turning raw materials into finished goods", "The direct use of natural resources, e.g. farming, fishing and mining"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "explain": "“Primary sector” means: The direct use of natural resources, e.g. farming, fishing and mining"}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets:match:77f0b38a', 'economics', 'economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets', '2.1 The Role of Markets', 'match', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Which definition matches the key term “Secondary sector”?", "options": ["Where quantity demanded exactly equals quantity supplied", "Concentrating on one particular task, product or industry", "Manufacturing and construction — turning raw materials into finished goods", "The direct use of natural resources, e.g. farming, fishing and mining"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "explain": "“Secondary sector” means: Manufacturing and construction — turning raw materials into finished goods"}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets:match:c9ebe59c', 'economics', 'economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets', '2.1 The Role of Markets', 'match', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Which definition matches the key term “Tertiary sector”?", "options": ["Where quantity demanded exactly equals quantity supplied", "The direct use of natural resources, e.g. farming, fishing and mining", "Activities that provide services, e.g. banking, education and tourism", "Tangible products that you can touch, like cars and phones"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "explain": "“Tertiary sector” means: Activities that provide services, e.g. banking, education and tourism"}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets:match:ea58668c', 'economics', 'economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets', '2.1 The Role of Markets', 'match', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Which definition matches the key term “Goods”?", "options": ["Manufacturing and construction — turning raw materials into finished goods", "Activities that provide services, e.g. banking, education and tourism", "Splitting a production process into tasks, each done by a specialist worker", "Tangible products that you can touch, like cars and phones"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "explain": "“Goods” means: Tangible products that you can touch, like cars and phones"}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets:match:e3b9aff6', 'economics', 'economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets', '2.1 The Role of Markets', 'match', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Which definition matches the key term “Services”?", "options": ["Concentrating on one particular task, product or industry", "How prices signal, ration and incentivise to allocate scarce resources", "Intangible products that you cannot touch, like education and finance", "Activities that provide services, e.g. banking, education and tourism"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "explain": "“Services” means: Intangible products that you cannot touch, like education and finance"}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets:match:a8cdeaef', 'economics', 'economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets', '2.1 The Role of Markets', 'match', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Which definition matches the key term “Factor market”?", "options": ["Where factors of production, such as labour, are bought and sold", "Concentrating on one particular task, product or industry", "How prices signal, ration and incentivise to allocate scarce resources", "Where quantity demanded exactly equals quantity supplied"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "“Factor market” means: Where factors of production, such as labour, are bought and sold"}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets:match:529ce956', 'economics', 'economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets', '2.1 The Role of Markets', 'match', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Which definition matches the key term “Product market”?", "options": ["Tangible products that you can touch, like cars and phones", "Where factors of production, such as labour, are bought and sold", "Where finished goods and services are sold to consumers and firms", "Trading products — needs at least one buyer and one seller"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "explain": "“Product market” means: Where finished goods and services are sold to consumers and firms"}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets:match:21cea031', 'economics', 'economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets', '2.1 The Role of Markets', 'match', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Which definition matches the key term “Derived demand”?", "options": ["Where quantity demanded exactly equals quantity supplied", "Splitting a production process into tasks, each done by a specialist worker", "How prices signal, ration and incentivise to allocate scarce resources", "Demand for a factor that comes from demand for the product it makes"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "explain": "“Derived demand” means: Demand for a factor that comes from demand for the product it makes"}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets:match:d7821939', 'economics', 'economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets', '2.1 The Role of Markets', 'match', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Which definition matches the key term “Specialisation”?", "options": ["Activities that provide services, e.g. banking, education and tourism", "Concentrating on one particular task, product or industry", "Where finished goods and services are sold to consumers and firms", "A way of bringing together buyers and sellers to exchange goods and services"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "“Specialisation” means: Concentrating on one particular task, product or industry"}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets:match:aebdcec7', 'economics', 'economics:2-1-the-role-of-markets', '2.1 The Role of Markets', 'match', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Which definition matches the key term “Division of labour”?", "options": ["Where factors of production, such as labour, are bought and sold", "Concentrating on one particular task, product or industry", "How prices signal, ration and incentivise to allocate scarce resources", "Splitting a production process into tasks, each done by a specialist worker"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "explain": "“Division of labour” means: Splitting a production process into tasks, each done by a specialist worker"}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-2-demand:exam:cfc1971d', 'economics', 'economics:2-2-demand', '2.2 Demand', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q1", "question": "Which one of the following causes an outward shift of the demand curve for restaurant meals?", "options": ["A fall in the price of restaurant meals", "A rise in incomes of consumers", "A rise in the price of restaurant meals", "A rise in the wages of restaurant staff"], "hint": "An OUTWARD (rightward) shift needs a NON-price factor. Two options are the meal''s own price (movement along), and one affects SUPPLY. What''s left?", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO2)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: B — A rise in incomes of consumers</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Higher incomes mean more meals demanded at every price — the whole curve shifts outward (right).</li>\n<li>A and C are changes in the meal''s own price: movements along the curve, not shifts.</li>\n<li>D raises restaurants'' costs — that affects the supply curve, not demand.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-2-demand:exam:00dd473a', 'economics', 'economics:2-2-demand', '2.2 Demand', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q2", "question": "This demand curve shows that...", "options": ["as consumers get better off, they buy more", "if consumers buy more, the price will rise", "if the price falls, consumers buy more", "if the price rises, producers will sell more"], "caseStudy": "<img src=\"/images/economics/2-2-demand-curve-q2-extracted.png\" alt=\"A demand curve from the OCR exam paper: Price on the vertical axis, Quantity on the horizontal axis, with a straight line labelled D sloping downwards from left to right\" style=\"display:block;width:100%;max-width:420px;margin:14px auto;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:8px;background:#fff;padding:6px;\" />", "hint": "The curve links the good''s own PRICE to QUANTITY demanded — nothing else. Which option only talks about those two things, in the right direction?", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO1 1b)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: C — if the price falls, consumers buy more</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>The downward slope IS the law of demand: lower price, higher quantity demanded.</li>\n<li>A is about income (a shift factor, not shown here); B reverses cause and effect; D describes supply behaviour.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-2-demand:exam:a065e20d', 'economics', 'economics:2-2-demand', '2.2 Demand', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q4", "question": "The demand for a product is more inelastic...", "options": ["the greater the time period under consideration", "the larger the number of substitutes available to consumers", "the more elastic the supply for this product", "the smaller the effect of a price change on the quantity demanded"], "hint": "Inelastic literally means quantity demanded barely responds to price. Which option SAYS that? (Time and substitutes both make demand MORE elastic.)", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO1 1b)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: D — the smaller the effect of a price change on the quantity demanded</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Inelastic demand = quantity demanded responds only a little to price changes — exactly what D describes.</li>\n<li>More time (A) and more substitutes (B) make demand MORE elastic; supply elasticity (C) is a separate concept.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-2-demand:exam:b7690c56', 'economics', 'economics:2-2-demand', '2.2 Demand', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q5", "question": "What will happen to the price and quantity of most goods due to a movement along the demand curve?", "options": ["price and quantity will change in opposite directions", "price and quantity will change in the same direction", "price will change, but quantity will stay the same", "quantity will change, but price will stay the same"], "hint": "The demand curve slopes DOWNWARDS. Moving along it, when price goes up, what happens to quantity demanded?", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO1b)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: A — price and quantity will change in opposite directions</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Moving along a downward-sloping demand curve: price up → quantity demanded down, and vice versa — opposite directions.</li>\n</ul>\n<h5>Examiner''s Comments</h5>\n<p>Most of the candidates gave A as the correct response to this question.</p>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-2-demand:exam:3cdadd46', 'economics', 'economics:2-2-demand', '2.2 Demand', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q6", "question": "What is the price elasticity of demand, if a price decrease leads to an increase in total revenue?", "options": ["Perfectly price inelastic", "Price elastic", "Price inelastic", "Unitary price elastic"], "hint": "Revenue rose even though each unit now sells for LESS — so the quantity sold must have risen by a BIGGER percentage than the price fell. What is that called?", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO1b)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: B — Price elastic</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Cutting price only raises total revenue when the % rise in quantity beats the % fall in price — that is elastic demand (PED &gt; 1). This is the revenue rule.</li>\n</ul>\n<h5>Examiner''s Comments</h5>\n<p>Most of the candidates gave B as the correct response to this question.</p>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-2-demand:exam:13ae0d5a', 'economics', 'economics:2-2-demand', '2.2 Demand', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q7", "question": "The demand for carrots is...", "options": ["perfectly price inelastic", "price elastic", "price inelastic", "unitary price elastic"], "caseStudy": "<p>A farmer sells bags of carrots. When the price is reduced from £2.00 per bag to £1.50, the quantity sold increases by 15%.</p>", "hint": "Work out the % price change first: 50p off £2.00 = 25%. Quantity rose only 15%. PED = 15 ÷ 25 = 0.6. Bigger or smaller than 1?", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO2)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: C — price inelastic</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Price falls 25% (£2.00 → £1.50) but quantity rises only 15%.</li>\n<li>PED = 15% ÷ 25% = 0.6 — less than 1, so demand is price inelastic.</li>\n</ul>\n<h5>Examiner''s Comments</h5>\n<p>Nearly half of the candidates gave the correct answer C with many thinking it was elastic while A and D also received support.</p>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-2-demand:exam:ff77f093', 'economics', 'economics:2-2-demand', '2.2 Demand', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q8", "question": "What does Diagram Z show?", "options": ["Changes in tastes of consumers", "Market demand of consumers", "Perfectly inelastic demand", "Shift in the demand curve"], "caseStudy": "<img src=\"/images/economics/2-2-individual-market-demand-extracted.png\" alt=\"Three demand diagrams from the OCR exam paper. Diagram X: a steep demand curve for Consumer A. Diagram Y: a flat demand curve for Consumer B. Diagram Z: a combined demand curve for Consumers A+B\" style=\"display:block;width:100%;max-width:520px;margin:14px auto;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:8px;background:#fff;padding:6px;\" />", "hint": "Look at the labels underneath: Consumer A, Consumer B... and Consumers A+B. What do you get when you ADD individual demands together?", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO2)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: B — Market demand of consumers</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Diagram Z is labelled \"Consumers A+B\" — the individual demands of A and B added together, which is the definition of market demand.</li>\n</ul>\n<h5>Examiner''s Comments</h5>\n<p>Most of the candidates gave B as the correct response to this question.</p>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-2-demand:exam:16122e31', 'economics', 'economics:2-2-demand', '2.2 Demand', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q9", "question": "The demand curve for plums will shift to the right if there is...", "options": ["a fall in the price of apples", "a fall in the price of plums", "a rise in the price of apples", "a rise in the price of plums"], "caseStudy": "<p>Apples and plums are substitute goods.</p>", "hint": "Two rules: plums'' OWN price can never shift the plum demand curve (that''s a movement along), and buyers switch to plums when the SUBSTITUTE gets dearer.", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO1b)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: C — a rise in the price of apples</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Dearer apples push shoppers towards the substitute — more plums demanded at every price, shifting the plum demand curve right.</li>\n<li>B and D are plums'' own price (movements along the curve); A would shift plum demand LEFT.</li>\n</ul>\n<h5>Examiner''s Comments</h5>\n<p>A high percentage of candidates gave Option C as the correct response to this question.</p>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-2-demand:exam:7dfab328', 'economics', 'economics:2-2-demand', '2.2 Demand', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q14", "question": "This suggests that the demand for haddock is...", "options": ["perfectly price elastic", "perfectly price inelastic", "price elastic", "unitary price elastic"], "caseStudy": "<p>A fishmonger reduces the price of haddock by 20%. As a result of this they sell 30 pieces of haddock instead of 20.</p>", "hint": "Sales rose from 20 to 30 — that''s +50%. Price fell 20%. PED = 50 ÷ 20 = 2.5. Bigger than 1 means...?", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO2)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: C — price elastic</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Quantity rises 50% (20 → 30 pieces) for a 20% price cut.</li>\n<li>PED = 50% ÷ 20% = 2.5 — greater than 1, so demand is price elastic.</li>\n</ul>\n<h5>Examiner''s Comments</h5>\n<p>Most candidates gave Option C as the correct response to this question.</p>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb)
